In order to obtain information about effect of NGQD on thermal stability of CCS, the TGA curve has been achieved. Thermal behavior of NGQD surveyed by TGA (inserted in Fig. 4
                        ) and it showed the same result with the previous report [38]. Fig. 4 shows the thermogravimetric of CCS before and after loading NGQD. The thermal behavior of the CCS and its NCs involves a single main decomposition process into the 250–500 °C. In these curves, a low temperature dehydration stage (100–250 °C) due to the loss of the physisorbed and interlayer water without disintegration of the structure (weight loss of ˂5%) and a high temperature decomposition stage (~250–500 °C) due to the breakage of main chain and the decomposition of glucose unites (weight loss of ˂60%) are observed. As can be seen in Table 1
                        , degradation temperature with 5% weight loss (T

                           d5
                        ), degradation temperature with 10% weight loss (T

                           d10
                        ) and char yield (CY) of the CCS/NGQD NCs are located at high values with respect to the CCS matrix. Also, CCS presents a char yield in around 34 °C, which increased to 42 °C with presence of 8 wt% of NGQD into the CCS matrix. On the other hand, compared with the thermal curve of pure CS [46], the thermogram of CCS exhibited higher thermal stability at T5, T10 and CY, which can be related to decrease intra-molecular interaction among the CS chains and increase array and inter-molecular interaction after cross-linking of the CS chains. These improvements in thermal stability of CCS after inserting different percentages of NGQD and slower degradation rate in the obtained NCs could be due to the interfacial interactions between the CCS and the functional groups of NGQD.
